fers to the medieval medical practice of bleeding, typically by applying leeches to a patient. The surname is recorded in the late 14th-century Poll Tax Returns for men whose occupation is stated as <i>medicus</i> ‘physician’, or occasionally <i>spicer</i> (spicers acted as apothecaries), but some men named <i>le Leche</i> have unrelated occupations including <i>cultor</i> ‘cultivator, farm laborer’, which suggests that <i>leche</i> could refer to an amateur ‘medicine man’ who supplied folk remedies."]},{"name":"Litch","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Leitch  ."]}]},{"name":"Cecily","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular English form of   Cecilia ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cecilie","meanings":["Medieval vernacular English form of   Cecilia ."]},{"name":"Cicely","meanings":["Variant of   Cecily .  This was a common form of the name in the Middle Ages, and in the 20th century was well known as the name of the British actress and singer  Cicely Courtneidge  (  1893–1980 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":20,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":33,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Cecily Leitch was born in 1295, in Paston, Norfolk, England, her father, William Leitch, was 20 and her mother, Cecily, was 11. Sh